In addition to confirming that at least some dinosaurs were feathered, a theory already widespread, it also provides specific data that fossils generally do not offer, such as their color and three-dimensional structure.
According to specialists, this animal has chestnut-colored plumage on the upper area and a pale or carotenoid hue on the lower part.
Likewise, the finding allows for a better understanding of the evolution of bird feathers.
Given that dinosaur feathers do not have a well-developed shaft, called a rachis, but do present other features of feathers (bristles and barbules), researchers have concluded that it is likely that the rachis is the result of a subsequent evolutionary development of these other characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that its function was not related to flight, but rather it was used to regulate temperature or as an indicator of the same. The researchers maintain that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample analyzed exhibits features of the plumage of an adult and not of a chick
The experts' assessments were that, even though it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample illustrates more the plumage of an adult than that of a chick.
